The directory is empty, so I'll provide the implementation pattern directly. Here's how to set up global error handling with `IExceptionHandler`:

**1. Create `Middleware/ApiExceptionHandler.cs`:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Diagnostics;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

namespace YourApp.Middleware;

internal sealed class ApiExceptionHandler(ILogger<ApiExceptionHandler> logger)
    : IExceptionHandler
{
    public async ValueTask<bool> TryHandleAsync(
        HttpContext httpContext,
        Exception exception,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        var (statusCode, title) = exception switch
        {
            KeyNotFoundException => (StatusCodes.Status404NotFound, "Not Found"),
            ArgumentException => (StatusCodes.Status400BadRequest, "Bad Request"),
            InvalidOperationException => (StatusCodes.Status409Conflict, "Conflict"),
            _ => (0, (string?)null)
        };

        if (statusCode == 0)
            return false; // Let the default handler return 500

        logger.LogWarning(exception, "Handled API exception: {Title}", title);

        httpContext.Response.StatusCode = statusCode;
        await httpContext.Response.WriteAsJsonAsync(new ProblemDetails
        {
            Status = statusCode,
            Title = title,
            Detail = title, // Don't use exception.Message — may leak internals
            Instance = httpContext.Request.Path
        }, cancellationToken);

        return true;
    }
}
```

**2. Register in `Program.cs`:**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<ApiExceptionHandler>();
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();

var app = builder.Build();

app.UseExceptionHandler();  // Catches unhandled exceptions → 500 ProblemDetails
app.UseStatusCodePages();   // Non-exception error status codes → ProblemDetails

// ... map your endpoints
```

**How it works:**

- `AddProblemDetails()` configures the default handler to return RFC 7807 JSON for unhandled exceptions (500) with no sensitive details.
- Your custom `IExceptionHandler` intercepts known exception types and maps them to specific status codes.
- Returning `false` for unknown exceptions lets the built-in handler produce a safe 500 response.
- No try-catch needed in endpoints — just `throw` from your service layer.

**Example 500 response (automatic, no details leaked):**

```json
{
  "type": "https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc9110#section-15.6.1",
  "title": "An error occurred while processing your request.",
  "status": 500
}
```

This requires .NET 8+. The middleware runs for every request, so all endpoints get consistent error formatting automatically.
